{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel0 \b \fs36 Optional Rules\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By its nature Minimal OpenD6 is highly customizable. With just a few choices you can change it from a light hearted game of keystone cops to gritty survival horror. While it is always good to remember that all rules are optional when preparing for the game the following ideas are meant to help give you further inspiration in adjusting the game to best fit your needs. In the end the only hard and fast rule is to play the game the way your group enjoys.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Renaming Attributes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By changing attribute names GMs can influence how a game feels. For Swashbuckling games the four attributes could be called Power, Grace, Reason, and Poise. If set in 70's Grindhouse they could transform into Muscles, Moves, Brains, and Cool.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Varying the Number of Attribute Dice\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Default starting player characters have 12 dice to spend on attributes. This makes them heroic in nature and generally competent in everything. By changing the number of attribute dice the feel of play is altered. The following chart provides guidelines for total attribute dice to use based on the power scale of the game:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 8 dice = The common man.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 9 dice = Experienced. Well trained in their specialty.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 10 dice = Competent. A cut above John Q Public.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 11 dice = Veteran. Easily stands out from the rest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 12 dice = Heroic. The default level of play.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 13 dice = World Class. Has an edge in most everything.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 14+ dice = Legendary characters. Herculean in nature.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Expanded Number of Attributes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The default four attributes cover most situations a character might come across. This also makes them fairly broad. If a greater division is desired extra attributes can be added. Examples include Perception (separated from Wit), Mechanical (from Agility and Wit), Courage (from Charm) and Toughness (from Might).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Beginning Attribute Dice:} When adding extra attributes each player receives three additional dice per attribute added for heroic level games. If 6 attributes are used in place of 4, players would divide 18D among them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects on Skills:} If your GM has increased the number of attributes he will provide you with a breakdown of where each skill now defaults.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Increasing the Attribute Range\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Characters are normally limited to 4D in an attribute unless a perk modifies this. Some GMs may wish to offer an upper maximum of 5D, 6D, or higher. When using this option the dice are spent as normal. Other GMs may not be so comfortable with such casually powerful characters. They may choose a more costly option instead.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Higher Attributes at a Price\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Under this rule characters can select attributes above 4D or whatever limits the GM sets, but they cost twice as much as normal beyond that limit. For example, a GM declares attributes are purchased as normal up to 4D but he allows higher attributes at a price up to 5D. A character who spends 6D in Might would record 5D as their Might attribute. Another character wants an Agility of 4D+2. This would cost him 5D+1 attribute dice.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 No Attributes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 All skills default to a base 2D and at character creation players receive 16D to spend on skills. Up to 4D can be spent in any one skill. For example, if playing a Gunslinger, the player may spend 4D in {\i Pistol}, 1D in {\i Rifle}, 3D in {\i Toughness} (to resist damage) 4D in {\i Dodge}, 3D in {\i Brawling}, and 1D in {\i Gamble}; recording it like this:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Gunslinger:} 5D Brawl, 6D Dodge, 3D Gamble, 6D Pistol, 3D Rifle, 5D Toughness.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Adding Paranormal Abilities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Paranormal Abilities are special for two reasons; first it is possible to have 0D in them, representing mundane characters. The second is that those who do have them gain access to restricted powers. For example in a vampire game characters might use Blood Potency, Dominate, Foretelling, Spirit, and Transformation; during character creation the player could spend attribute dice to gain some access to one or more them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 No extra attribute dice are given for Paranormal Abilities at character creation. This reduces a character's mundane attributes but the powers granted by their paranormal gifts make up for it. GMs will define which, if any, are used in their games and how they work in the setting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Characters who begin with 0D in a Paranormal Ability may be allowed to purchase it later with GM permission. We suggest the first die cost 10 or 20 CP.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Quasi Skills\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These are purchased as attributes at character creation but afterwards are raised with CP like skills and don't have any skills under them. GMs might increase the cost to raise these skills based on a character's access to teachers or suitable training material. For example, a game focused on Angels might include the quasi skills of {\i Spiritual}, {\i Etheric}, and {\i Corporeal}. A starting character may have {\i Spiritual} 2D {\i Etheric} 1D, and {\i Corporeal} 0D. Later, studying under one of his elder's the angel would spend 2 CP to improve Spiritual to 2D+1.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Paranormal Attributes with Skills\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These are the same as any other attributes except that characters can have 0D in the attribute and no access to their related skills. In a game focused on werewolf naturists the GM might create the attributes Elemental and Spiritual. Under the Elemental attribute the skills may be {\i Air}, {\i Earth}, {\i Fire}, and {\i Water}; while Spiritual includes {\i Communing}, {\i Summoning}, and {\i Channeling}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Varying Starting Skill Dice\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Default starting player characters receive 7 dice to spend on skills and perks and can't spend more than 2D on any one skill. This represents fledgling heroic level characters. The GM might grant them additional dice for a more difficult campaign. He may also allow them to spend more than 2D in any single skill. The number of dice and maximum allocations should be weighed carefully to fit the desires of the campaign.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 High Skills Rolls Increasing Damage\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When using this rule damage is boosted by 1 point for every 5 points you exceeded the target number to hit. If a warrior needed to beat a Parry of 14 and rolled a 26 on his attack, this would increase the damage by +2 since the target was beaten by 12.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For increased deadliness, simply reduce the number needed to exceed the roll by to increase damage. If every 3 points of success translates to 1 point of damage skilled characters are deadly.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Independent Skills\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Skills normally always default to one particular attribute, for example {\i Sword} always defaults to Might. In a more freewheeling campaign skills may be detached from attributes allowing more fluid definition of how their used. When skills are purchased they don't get the benefit of any default attribute. If using a broad skill list then the typical 7D may be used. If opting for many more narrowly focused skills then 12D to 18D may be appropriate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It is suggested that raising skills with CP should cost double the normal price for skill advancement. This sounds more costly but isn't because the skills start so much lower.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A sample knight might look like this:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Knight:} Might 4D, Agility 3D, Wit 2D, Charm 3D\line \u160 ?\u160 ?\u160 ?\u160 ?\u160 ?\u160 ?\u160 ?\u160 ?Dodge 1D, History 1D, Ride 2D, Seduce 1D, Sword 2D\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When attacking an enemy our knight will typically roll Might + {\i Sword} for a total of 6D. Later when attempting to purchase a quality sword in the market the knight would roll his Wit + {\i Sword} for a total of 4D. That evening while practicing his swordsmanship a group of ladies watches from afar. To impress them he rolls his Charm + {\i Sword} for a total of 5D.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Rolling Limit\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some dislike rolling large numbers of dice, feeling the math slows down the game. GMs may impose a limit on the number of dice rolled at any time. We suggest the cut-off be 5 dice. If a character has more than 5D on a roll, each die beyond the rolling limit is converted to a +3 bonus. For example a GM has imposed a 5D rolling limit at his table. A character with 7D+1 in {\i Rifle} shoots at bad guy. He rolls 5 dice and adds 7 to the result.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Halfway There\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To help speed up the game, if the number of skill dice in any skill is equal to half the Target Number, the GM may consider it an automatic success.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Traditional OpenD6 Hero Points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In traditional OpenD6, Hero Points work differently. Instead of giving a static +6 to a roll and allowing for other options such as Flesh Wounds, etc. they double the number of dice on any single roll. For example a spy has 4D+1 in {\i Security} and must disable a bomb. To help ensure success the player spends 1 HP doubling his roll to 8D+2.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Traditional OpenD6 Character Points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In traditional OpenD6 Character Points may be spent to improve individual rolls during play. These points can be spent after the character has rolled but only before the GM has let the player know if the roll was successful. Each CP spent grants additional Wild Die to the roll. The GM may impose a limit on how many CP may be used on a single roll in his game. Players cannot spend character points to improve a roll that they also spent a Hero Point on.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Traditional OpenD6 Might Damage\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In traditional OpenD6 the base amount of damage dealt in unarmed and melee combat is calculated differently. Characters use half their dice in their {\i Lift} skill ignoring pips and rounding down the result. For example, a character with a {\i Lift} skill of 3D+2 would deal 1D damage in unarmed combat or 1D+weapon damage when using a melee weapon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Buying New Perks\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you have a good reason and the GM agrees you may buy a perk after play has begun for 10 CP times the standard cost. Some perks make no sense; you don't wake up an elf.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Buying Off Complications\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To get rid of a complication the GM will impose a price of at least 20 CP if he allows it at all and you need a really good story, possibly even a quest or adventure to justify it. Alternatively, as the story progresses player and GM might agree to exchange old complications for new one.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Body Points (alternative to Wound Levels)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In place of using Wound Levels GMs may elect to use Body Points (BP). Under this variant, players roll their character's Might and add this to 20. This is the amount of damage they can take before death. If less variability is desired the GM may give 4 BP per die in Might instead.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Damage Resistance Under Fast Static Combat:} Under this combat system, the Static Soak is replaced with Static Damage Resistance (DR). Static Damage Resistance is equal to the Armor Value of the target. As a rule of thumb any creature or stock character with no number in parenthesis next to their Soak has a Damage Resistance of 0; those that do subtract their Soak from the number in parenthesis and use the difference. The GM might define special abilities that also grant a bonus to this total. Hero points can be spent to gain a +6 bonus to DR.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Damage Resistance Traditional OpenD6 Combat:} The damage resistance total equals a roll of the target character's die codes from armor or Special Abilities. Hero points can be spent to gain a +6 bonus to DR.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Taking Damage Under Both Systems:} When a character is hit they subtract their DR from the damage total. If the remaining total is one or more it is subtracted from the character's current BP total. If reduced to 0 or fewer BP, the character is dead.\par}
